pt to keep their options open. This provisional way of living—of always looking elsewhere, to the future, to other people, to other ways of being, and never committing to what one has, or else putting in the time and energy to achieve what one wants—is a big mistake, and Life Is Short tells readers how to avoid this trap.By reminding us how extraordinary it is not that we have so little time but that we have any at all, Life Is Short challenges us to rethink what makes life meaningful and how to make the most of it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aLife. 0aTime management. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aAbsurdity.  aActivation.  aActive imagination.  aAdult.  aAkrasia.  aAlbert Camus.  aAmerican Psychiatric Association.  aAnthropomorphism.  aApostrophe.  aArchetype.  aAscending and Descending.  aAubade.  aAwareness.  aBehavior.  aBiology.  aBody dysmorphic disorder.  aBulletproofing.  aCambridge University Press.  aCarl Jung.  aCertainty.  aChild prodigy.  aCluster B personality disorders.  aConcoction.  aConsciousness.  aCycles of Time.  aDaydream.  aDemiurge.  aDerek Parfit.  aDisease.  aEleusinian Mysteries.  aEpicurus.  aEternal return.  aEthics.  aExistence.  aFreedom of speech.  aGerontology.  aGnosticism.  aGrandiosity.  aHarold Bloom.  aHenry Wadsworth Longfellow.  aIdentity (social science).  aImaginary audience.  aIndividuation.  aInstant.  aJ. M. Barrie.  aJean-Paul Sartre.  aLeaves of Grass.  aLorenzo Da Ponte.  aM. C. Escher.  aMarie-Louise von Franz.  aMathematician.  aMeaningful life.  aMichel Houellebecq.  aMicrosoft.  aMysterium Coniunctionis.  aNarcissism.  aNatural approach.  aNeurosis.  aObstacle.  aOtto Rank.  aParagraph.  aPenguin Classics.  aPerfectionism (psychology